Local Explanations of Breast Cancer Severity Models using SHAP¶

The UCI ML Breast Cancer Wisconsin dataset, provided in sci-kit learn package, was created based on results of FNA procedure which 569 patients underwent to asses the severity of their breast cancer. Because the FNA procedure results in an image, the experts encoded 30 variables out of it to create tabular data. Detailed information, including simple exploratory analysis and modelling, can be found in previous report on this topic or Sci-Kit Learn Documentation.

The target variable in this dataset is binary, meaning it encodes:

  • patients with malignant tumor as 0,
  • patients with benign tumor as 1,

and there are no other classes of interest present in this task.

The aim of this report is to:

  • create 2 simple models for solving the task (including 1 tree based),
  • explain the predictions of the model locally using SHAP.

Sections 1-3 are done using solely an xgboost models, whereas in section 4 I compare xgboost to multi-layered perceptron model.

1. Local explanation of distinctive prediction cases¶

In this section I decided to analyse explanations from 3 distinctive cases:

  • an example of patient with malignant tumor predicted as benign,
  • an example of patient with correctly identified malignant tumor,
  • an example of patient with correctly identified benign tumor.

The first interesting information we can derive from the plot is that worst type features are high contributors for this particular prediction. For recollection, in the previous report I found out that worst type features have no dependency with target variable whatsoever (in a global sense), and yet there are examples that actually need them for confident prediction.

Similar behaviour can be observed for this example of correct malignant tumor prediction. Moreover, worst area feature shows a high predictive power in this case. This observation can also lead us to hypothesis that tumors with enlarged cells (in this case worst area is the area of the largest cell) may be a sign of malignant tumor or fast tumor growth, which could be consulted with a domain expert in the further iterations of ML model implementation.

Finally, for the comparison, we can see an example of malignant tumor predicted incorrectly as benign. Again, worst area plays a significant role in prediction, but this time its value is relatively small, which could have contributed to the confusion of the model. Similarly worst perimeter is relatively small, and resemble more the explanation for the benign tumor than the malignant one.

2. Analysing features of highest importance across predictions¶

Another observation we can derive from local explanations is the fact that there are no consistent "most important" features in predictions of examples. In section 1, we saw the examples in which worst area and worst perimeter were the ones with highest contribution, and yet there are also examples that surprisingly use worst texture or mean/worst concave points as indicator of specific type of tumor.

An interesting hypothesis that I can derive here is the question of importance of feature selection in the problems of high imbalance in target variable. Although many of those features did not have any global dependence or correlation with target variable, they seem to be of high importance in classification of malignant tumors which are generally less represented in the dataset. The example of patient 47 (above) is particularly interesting because it uses a rare combination of high important features (which could indicate it might be a problematic example and keeping all the features without selection actually helped in correct classification).

3. Analysing contribution mismatch within same feature¶

The already mentioned example of patients with correctly and incorrectly classified malignant tumor is also the example of contribution mismatch of the same feature.

In the case of patient 29, worst area is a very large indicator of malignant tumor due to its relatively high value, whereas for patient 41 the smaller worst area led the model to believe the tumor is benign.

4. Analysing feature contribution across models¶

Another interesting comparison would be to analyze prediction for patient 41 - which XGBoost predicted incorrectly, but MLP Classifier correctly. We can see that XGBoost focused more on worst area and worst perimeter and due to their relatively lower value confused example with benign tumor (which is a similar behaviour to other examples which focused on those 2 features and had relatively low values and were true benign examples). However, for this particular example, MLP changed the strategy and actually used worst texture and worst smoothness the most, which made it realize the example was in fact a case of malignant tumor.

Closing remarks¶

Local analysis of model predictions using SHAP allowed us to uncover some interesting hypothesis about the data.

The most crucial one for me is the question of using feature selection in a scenario of high imbalance. SHAP analysis uncovered that in many cases, even if the feature did not have any global correlation or dependency with target variable, it was necessary for correct classification of more complex examples (that often were also of higher interest because they were malignant cases).

Moreover, for example for patient 47, SHAP uncovered a very rare combination of contributing features (with respect to other combinations from other examples), which could be analysed further by domain experts to get more insights about the dataset.

Finally, the analysis could give us some ideas for creating new features. For example, locally in multiple examples, worst area of cells is a high contributing indicator for malignant/benign discrimination, which could maybe suggest a faster/slower growth of a tumor and hence the prediction. It could be verified, with the help of domain expert, if a new growth-related proxy feature could be also helpful in further model creation.
